Optimizing Retail Revenue¶

1. Sales & Gross Income by Branch/City¶

In [6]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Group data
sales_by_location = df.groupby(['Branch', 'City'])[['Total', 'gross income']].sum().reset_index()

# Create a combined label for x-axis
sales_by_location['Branch_City'] = sales_by_location['Branch'] + ' - ' + sales_by_location['City']

# Plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(16, 6))

# Total Sales
ax[0].bar(sales_by_location['Branch_City'], sales_by_location['Total'], color='skyblue')
ax[0].set_title('Total Sales by Branch/City')
ax[0].tick_params(axis='x', rotation=45)

# Gross Income
ax[1].bar(sales_by_location['Branch_City'], sales_by_location['gross income'], color='orange')
ax[1].set_title('Gross Income by Branch/City')
ax[1].tick_params(axis='x', rotation=45)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig("sales and gross income.png")
plt.show()

4. Member vs Regular Customer Spending¶

In [13]:
member_spending = df.groupby('Customer type')['Total'].agg(['mean', 'sum'])
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 5))
member_spending['mean'].plot(kind='bar', ax=ax[0], title='Average Spend by Customer Type', color=['blue', 'red'])
member_spending['sum'].plot(kind='pie', ax=ax[1], autopct='%1.1f%%', title='Total Revenue by Customer Type')
plt.savefig("members vs regular customer.png")
plt.show()

9. Tax 5% Consistency Check¶

In [23]:
# Verify tax = 5% of Total
df['Calculated Tax'] = df['Total'] * 0.05
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
plt.plot(df['Tax 5%'], df['Calculated Tax'], 'o', alpha=0.3)
plt.plot([0, max(df['Tax 5%'])], [0, max(df['Tax 5%'])], 'r--')
plt.title('Tax 5% vs Calculated Tax')
plt.xlabel('Actual Tax')
plt.ylabel('Expected Tax')
plt.savefig("tax.png")
plt.show()

10. Peak Sales Times¶

In [39]:
# Convert Time column with explicit format (e.g., "HH:MM")
df['Hour'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Time'], format='%H:%M').dt.hour  # Use format matching your data

# Plot hourly sales
hourly_sales = df.groupby('Hour')['Total'].sum()
hourly_sales.plot(kind='line', marker='o', figsize=(10, 5), title='Total Sales by Hour of Day')
plt.ylabel('Total Sales')
plt.xticks(range(0, 24))  # Ensure all hours are shown
plt.grid(True)
plt.savefig("peak sales.png")
plt.show()
